The paper focuses on mobile edge computing (MEC) and its performance optimization through a game theory-based approach. This involves the joint decision-making of task offloading and resource allocation, which is relevant to the networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The use of game theory also suggests a potential fit with the game theory and economics (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the management of interference in the network, which could relate to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category. The algorithmic and computational aspects of the approach could also be relevant to the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category, as well as the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
